answers.body_markdown:
The only difference worth worrying about is in terms of code maintainability. Generally, [variables should live in the smallest scope possible](https://softwareengineering.stackexchange.com/questions/388052/rationale-to-prefer-local-variables-over-instance-variables). This can make the code easier to read. For example:

&gt;These aren&#39;t functionally identical if the anonymous function is called multiple times but for the sake of argument lets say it will only be called once.

Without you *explicitly saying that*, a reader of the code would likely think that there&#39;s at least a possibility of `fn` being called more than once (otherwise, what&#39;s the point of the outer scope variable?).

Or, imagine if there was more code in the function: compare

```
function fn () {
  // a moderate amount of code
  return something(cb =&gt; {
    // a moderate amount of code
    let i = 0
    setInterval(() =&gt; cb(i++), 1000)
  })
}
```

to

```
function fn () {
  let i = 0
  // a moderate amount of code
  return something(cb =&gt; {
    // a moderate amount of code
    setInterval(() =&gt; cb(i++), 1000)
  })
}
```

The first version is probably preferable, because the declaration of the variable is very close to where it&#39;s being used, which is not the case for the second version.

Another difference between them is that, the farther up the scope chain the interpreter has to look to find a variable reference, the longer it&#39;ll take to process, at least in some circumstances. This is completely insignificant in almost all cases, but it&#39;s still a potential difference: compare https://jsfiddle.net/pa2v9xuj/ to https://jsfiddle.net/wzo7bgve/

